WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:29.079 --> 00:32.173
- Yes, sir. Where to?
- It's the train to Chicago. The Silver Streak.

00:32.173 --> 00:34.979
- Silver Streak. I'll take care of your bags, sir.
- Thank you.

00:36.053 --> 00:38.613
- Thank you.
- Thank you. Thanks

00:49.499 --> 00:52.366
What are those conventioneers
doing up at the baggage car?

00:53.536 --> 00:55.265
Mmm, mmm, mmm.
Now, ain't that somethin'?

00:55.265 --> 00:57.772
I thought it was bad enough with the
hippies on board. Now we got their fathers.

01:01.211 --> 01:03.270
Oh, we had to get Mary Lou.

01:03.270 --> 01:07.339
- She's our date for the party.
- Come on, Conductor! Let's get this show on the track!

01:07.339 --> 01:09.281
Oh, ho, ho.
I beg your pardon, sir.

01:10.186 --> 01:12.780
Hello. Am I in the right place?

01:12.780 --> 01:15.825
First class. Yes, sir.
Right this way.

01:15.825 --> 01:17.553
Watch your step there.

01:29.638 --> 01:31.697
- This is your room here, sir.
- Okay, thanks a lot.

01:31.697 --> 01:33.434
- Thank you, sir. Have a pleasant trip.
- Bye-bye.

01:33.434 --> 01:38.241
Sir, you think you're gonna be needin'
all these bags up here? If not, I can store
some of'em down at the other end.

01:38.241 --> 01:41.111
- Sure, sure. All I need is this one and that one.
- Okay.

01:41.111 --> 01:43.082
- You can take this. I'll keep the briefcase.
- I'll take that.

01:44.482 --> 01:47.181
- Is this the bed?
- Yeah. I'll be makin' that up a little later on.

01:47.181 --> 01:49.087
Okay, thanks.

01:49.087 --> 01:52.320
- And this is...
- Your lavatory and sink, sir.

01:52.320 --> 01:55.056
- Nice, big room.
- Very convenient.

01:55.056 --> 01:58.394
- What's this partition?
- Oh, that turns the room into a double suite..

01:58.394 --> 02:01.526
We used to have a lot of calls for 'em...
from the honeymooners.

02:01.526 --> 02:03.229
I'm sorry.

02:03.229 --> 02:07.172
I'm not doing it on purpose.
This latch seems to be stuck.

02:08.876 --> 02:10.537
Everything's changed.
Did you say something?

02:10.979 --> 02:15.176
No! No. I-I agree with everything you said.
All I wanna do is take it easy.

02:15.176 --> 02:18.412
Good, good. Then just settle back
and enjoy the trip.

02:18.412 --> 02:22.047
Because it ain't gonna be too exciting,
now, but we'll get you there on time.

02:22.047 --> 02:23.818
- Okay. Have a nice rest.
- Thanks a lot.

02:23.818 --> 02:25.825
- Bye-bye.
- Good evening.

02:29.830 --> 02:31.660
Board!

03:31.790 --> 03:34.816
So long, L.A.! Bye!

03:56.381 --> 03:58.576
Do you like this perfume?

03:58.576 --> 04:00.583
I mix it myself.

04:02.854 --> 04:05.846
Lovely. Very nice.

04:15.699 --> 04:17.690
That's something, huh?
Yes, sir.

04:17.690 --> 04:19.963
We leave Los Angeles,

04:19.963 --> 04:23.006
and we go right up there to Nevada...

04:23.006 --> 04:25.598
into Colorado, across the Rockies...

04:25.598 --> 04:28.041
up to Kansas City, Kansas.

04:28.041 --> 04:31.308
Right in here's a town
called Ashland, Missouri.

04:31.308 --> 04:36.080
Cross the big Mississippi.
Two and a half days, right up
there in Chicago, Illinois.

04:36.080 --> 04:38.121
- That's some trip, huh?
- Mm-hmm.

04:38.121 --> 04:39.917
- You from Chicago?
- No, Los Angeles.

04:39.917 --> 04:42.015
I'm from Chicago.

04:42.015 --> 04:43.753
My name is Bob Sweet.

04:43.753 --> 04:46.887
A sweet man, but a mean baby.

04:46.887 --> 04:48.624
- George Caldwell.
- Yeah?

04:49.698 --> 04:52.258
Yeah, George,
what racket you in?

04:52.258 --> 04:55.599
- Publishing.
- No kidding? Come on. Sit down here.
- Thanks.

04:55.599 --> 04:58.401
You know, I'm in vitamins myself.

04:59.809 --> 05:02.744
Mm-hmm. Here.
There's a sample for ya. Vitamin "E."

05:02.744 --> 05:05.042
Now, that is great
for the old pecker.

05:07.716 --> 05:10.412
Yeah, it really keeps
the pencil sharp, and I'm not kiddin'.

05:10.412 --> 05:14.252
Have you had a chance yet
to check out the action?

05:14.252 --> 05:17.315
No. Actually, this is the first time
I've ever taken a train.

05:18.394 --> 05:20.328
- You're kidding me?
- No.

05:20.328 --> 05:21.048
Come on

05:22.398 --> 05:24.865
- Well, you're in for the ride of your life.
- Oh, yeah?

05:25.934 --> 05:29.961
You just pick out a little chickie, my friend...
and it's hug and munch all the way to Chicago.

05:31.272 --> 05:33.263
- Really?
- I do it all the time.

05:33.263 --> 05:38.210
I tell my boss that I'm afraid of flying...
and I get this action twice a year.

05:39.180 --> 05:41.705
It's a cathouse on wheels.

05:41.705 --> 05:43.876
No... Hey, listen.
Come on.

05:43.876 --> 05:48.651
It's something about the movement
of the train that does it.
All that motion makes a girl horny.

05:50.125 --> 05:53.891
Well, I'll tell you, Bob. I'm not really
interested in a shipboard romance.

05:53.891 --> 05:56.522
- I took the train to rest and get a lot
of reading done.
- Hold it, hold it.

05:56.522 --> 06:01.394
Right there, George.
I believe I see my chickie for tonight.

06:04.438 --> 06:07.771
Hi, there. Can I, uh,
buy you a drink?

06:08.609 --> 06:12.568
- I have one. Thank you.
- Well, I'll just, uh, join you then, huh?

06:12.568 --> 06:14.739
That's an old-fashioned, bartender.

06:20.120 --> 06:24.079
- You go all the way?
- What?

06:27.161 --> 06:30.597
I said, do you go all the way...
to Chicago?

06:32.466 --> 06:35.059
Oh. Yes, I do.

06:40.339 --> 06:43.137
- Well, then maybe we can do it together.
- Do what?

06:44.010 --> 06:48.140
- Go to Chicago.
I mean, you know, we're gonna be, uh...

06:48.140 --> 06:51.274
stuck on this train together,

06:51.274 --> 06:53.250
and we can't jump off.

06:55.755 --> 06:57.848
Do you feel that motion?

07:05.064 --> 07:06.964
Are you hot?

07:06.964 --> 07:07.684
What?

07:09.267 --> 07:11.235
I said, are you hot?

07:13.872 --> 07:16.568
Lady, I am always hot.

07:18.410 --> 07:20.708
Maybe I can cool you down.

08:08.259 --> 08:11.922
How's the latch? May I?

08:11.922 --> 08:14.021
Yes. Please, sit down.

08:15.065 --> 08:17.158
What a nice surprise.

08:18.234 --> 08:22.000
I said, how's the latch?
We have connecting rooms.

08:22.000 --> 08:24.904
The latch. Good.
It's good. It's fine. Thank you.

08:24.904 --> 08:29.206
It's a little bit rusty, but nothing serious.
I'll get the porter to look at it.

08:30.179 --> 08:32.703
There's no rush, is there?

08:36.085 --> 08:37.881
Would you folks like a cocktail?

08:38.955 --> 08:41.515
Uh, a martini on the rocks
with a twist.

08:42.792 --> 08:45.784
- Two.
- Yes, sir.

08:48.631 --> 08:52.532
- My name is George Caldwell.
- Hilly Burns.

08:53.702 --> 08:57.968
That's short for Hildegard.
What's that pencil for?

08:57.968 --> 09:01.567
Oh, you have to fill out
your own menu card.

09:04.012 --> 09:08.381
"One macedoine of fruit,
beef Oriental, rice, carrots...

09:08.381 --> 09:11.078
coffee, apple pie a la mode. "

09:12.154 --> 09:13.644
You print very well.

09:15.490 --> 09:16.479
Thanks.

09:17.492 --> 09:20.222
I'll have the same thing.
You do it for me.

09:23.498 --> 09:25.728
I can't even read my own writing.

09:25.728 --> 09:28.928
I don't do shorthand,
and I can't type.

09:28.928 --> 09:30.994
What do you do for a living?

09:30.994 --> 09:32.903
I'm a secretary.

09:34.141 --> 09:37.076
- Well, how do you keep your job?
- I give great phone.

09:40.381 --> 09:42.042
I have a terrific personality.

09:44.051 --> 09:46.815
- You going to Chicago?
- Yes.

09:46.815 --> 09:49.651
I'm going to my sister's wedding.

09:49.651 --> 09:52.090
How come you're taking the train?
You afraid of flying?

09:52.090 --> 09:55.526
No, I'm not afraid of flying.

09:55.526 --> 09:59.862
I, uh... I just want to be bored.

10:03.103 --> 10:05.230
And you?

10:05.230 --> 10:09.537
Oh, my new boss
likes the old-fashioned ways.

10:10.310 --> 10:13.108
He's just written a book
on Rembrandt...

10:13.108 --> 10:16.376
and he's gonna kick off his publicity
campaign with a lecture at the Art Institute.

10:16.376 --> 10:18.747
Oh, yes? I'm in publishing.
What's his name?

10:18.747 --> 10:21.252
Professor Arthur Schreiner.
Have you heard of him?

10:23.390 --> 10:25.654
Most people haven't.

10:25.654 --> 10:29.593
He's, um... He's been a recluse
working on this book for about  20  years.

10:29.593 --> 10:32.153
- Where is he now?
- Oh, he's in bed...

10:32.153 --> 10:35.599
with a glass of hot milk and molasses.
He's a health nut.

10:35.599 --> 10:39.159
- What do you publish?
- Oh, mostly nonfiction.

10:39.159 --> 10:42.298
Gardening, cook books,
how-to-do-it books.

10:43.809 --> 10:45.800
Like sex manuals?

10:47.179 --> 10:50.671
- I've edited a few.
- An authority, huh?

10:52.451 --> 10:55.750
I know what goes where...
and why.

10:58.257 --> 11:01.454
- That's very interesting. Are you married?
- Divorced.

11:02.428 --> 11:04.089
How come?

11:09.935 --> 11:12.494
My friends all told me that
my wife was too good for me...

11:12.494 --> 11:15.562
and after a couple of years
I decided they were right.

11:16.908 --> 11:18.375
Sounds sad.

11:20.244 --> 11:24.442
You say that your boss is in art history.
Is that what you're interested in?

11:25.516 --> 11:27.916
Not really.

11:27.916 --> 11:31.477
just got this job because
I was available. I was willing to travel.

11:33.958 --> 11:36.893
- Would you like some wine with this meal?
- Oh, what a question.

11:39.497 --> 11:43.126
Um, we'll have a bottle
of the Mouton Cadet.

11:46.503 --> 11:47.993
Very good, sir.

11:49.639 --> 11:53.234
- You do that very well.
- I give great French.

12:18.802 --> 12:21.099
- He'll never talk.
- We gotta find those papers.

12:21.099 --> 12:22.603
Come on.
We'll look in his compartment.

12:26.609 --> 12:29.476
So that was your introduction
to high society?

12:31.180 --> 12:33.648
Look, he was very good to me.

12:33.648 --> 12:36.708
He taught me everything
from the pill to Picasso.

12:37.520 --> 12:41.047
- What was missing?
- A marriage license.

12:41.924 --> 12:43.448
Is that what you want?

12:45.227 --> 12:47.161
I did then.

12:48.497 --> 12:50.397
Right now, I'd like some more
champagne.

12:56.871 --> 13:00.034
- Uh-oh. Shall I get another bottle?
- Two.

13:04.112 --> 13:06.774
This place seems to be closing down.

13:09.050 --> 13:12.076
Why don't we take our glasses...

13:12.076 --> 13:14.621
and go to our rooms?

13:18.760 --> 13:21.058
We could even open
the connecting door.

13:22.297 --> 13:24.231
We could even break down
the whole partition.

13:26.200 --> 13:29.726
- I'll speak to the porter.
- I'll get the champagne.

13:44.851 --> 13:46.944
You were right.
It's that motion.

13:46.944 --> 13:49.352
I didn't understand it,
but you were right.

13:52.326 --> 13:53.657
Good night.

14:10.209 --> 14:11.699
- Rapist!
- No, no, no, no!

14:12.260 --> 14:14.760
Pardonez-moi, por favor.

14:31.697 --> 14:33.221
Excuse me.

14:34.300 --> 14:35.995
Um, this won't take a minute.

14:36.936 --> 14:38.426
Good.

14:39.838 --> 14:41.806
Excellent. These are all right.

14:41.806 --> 14:43.306
Sorry. Good evening.

14:54.619 --> 14:55.339
Come in.

15:04.229 --> 15:06.390
This is very nice.

15:07.365 --> 15:10.425
- Would you like some champagne?
- Yes.

15:10.425 --> 15:13.834
I can't get over the size of this room
without the partition.

15:14.838 --> 15:20.043
They are small rooms by themselves.
They're perfect forjuggling.

15:20.043 --> 15:21.507
- For what?
- For juggling.

15:21.507 --> 15:24.410
When you practice, the balls would
always bounce off the walls.

15:26.682 --> 15:28.741
Do you juggle a lot?

15:30.019 --> 15:32.078
I know what goes where and why.

15:40.063 --> 15:42.054
I like that song.

15:43.332 --> 15:47.701
If I ever hear it again...
it'll be difficult not to think of you.

15:49.371 --> 15:52.863
- You put that very nicely.
- Thanks.

16:02.217 --> 16:04.947
To traveling by train.

16:04.947 --> 16:07.386
Trains that pass in the night.

16:26.574 --> 16:28.439
You like my new shoes?

16:28.439 --> 16:31.706
- Yes, I do.
- Why don't you take them off?

16:31.706 --> 16:35.909
You can put them in that little locker over there...
and the porter will have them shined for you
in the morning.

16:35.909 --> 16:38.975
- Really?
- That's terrific.

16:44.425 --> 16:46.416
- Is that the master's work?
- Mm-hmm.

16:48.529 --> 16:51.123
He gave me this copy
for safe keeping.

16:52.133 --> 16:53.828
Do you want to read it?

17:26.098 --> 17:27.760
Slide over.

17:33.572 --> 17:35.563
It's beautiful, isn't it?

17:36.575 --> 17:38.236
Very.

17:53.559 --> 17:56.392
Do you really edit sex manuals?

17:57.529 --> 18:00.191
I really, really do.

18:01.500 --> 18:03.661
But I have a confession to make.

18:04.736 --> 18:07.932
I'm much better
at books on gardening.

18:07.932 --> 18:10.997
- Really?
- That's my specialty.

18:13.511 --> 18:15.172
Well...

18:16.547 --> 18:20.574
is there anything that
you might wanna pass on?

18:22.820 --> 18:25.516
- You mean about gardening?
- Yes.

18:26.324 --> 18:30.158
Some helpful hints
for the beginner.

18:31.662 --> 18:33.323
Well...

18:35.600 --> 18:37.659
One tip is...

18:38.736 --> 18:41.670
always be nasty to nasturtiums.

18:43.106 --> 18:45.336
- Is that so?
- They love that.

18:45.336 --> 18:48.707
- They like it rough?
- The rougher, the better.

18:48.707 --> 18:50.370
Great.

18:54.384 --> 18:56.318
What else should I know?

18:57.687 --> 19:00.656
I could teach you the secret
of how to treat azaleas.

19:00.656 --> 19:02.783
Oh, tell me.
I'm all ears.

19:02.783 --> 19:05.157
I can see that.

19:05.157 --> 19:06.752
Well...

19:07.631 --> 19:11.089
just treat them the same way
as you would a begonia.

19:11.089 --> 19:14.762
- No kidding?
- That's gospel.

19:14.762 --> 19:18.568
You mean what you're saying is what's
good for azaleas is good for begonias?

19:18.568 --> 19:22.407
- You got it.
- George, this is fascinating.

19:22.407 --> 19:24.912
I thought you'd be interested.

19:24.912 --> 19:27.642
I'd like to delve deeper.

19:27.642 --> 19:30.617
- Be my guest.
- Thank you.

19:44.767 --> 19:48.931
What would happen if you treated
an azalea like a nasturtium?

19:51.039 --> 19:54.031
Now, this is the really interesting part.

20:05.320 --> 20:08.118
- What is it, George?
- Did you see it? Did you see that man?

20:08.118 --> 20:11.556
- What man?
- There was a man
hanging outside this window.

20:11.556 --> 20:14.390
- He was shot in the head.
- What?

20:14.390 --> 20:18.159
Hilly, a dead man
fell off the roof.

20:18.159 --> 20:21.963
I saw it. His coat was stuck.

20:26.540 --> 20:29.373
Oh. I should do something.

20:29.373 --> 20:32.537
I should report it.
Maybe they could stop the train.

20:32.537 --> 20:35.513
George, I'm sure
you saw something.

20:35.513 --> 20:39.109
You probably saw a kid's kite
or an old newspaper out...

20:39.109 --> 20:43.520
Look! Like that. You see, George,
it could have been anything out there.

20:44.758 --> 20:47.192
But his eyes were so clear.

20:48.261 --> 20:50.695
I think they were clearer
than your head.

20:50.695 --> 20:53.528
- You imagined this, George.
- I didn't. I know I didn't.

20:53.528 --> 20:56.660
Then why don't you call the conductor
and tell him your story?

20:58.672 --> 21:01.970
- I feel dizzy.
- You know what? Here.

21:01.970 --> 21:04.032
Lie down here, George.

21:07.079 --> 21:10.378
Whew! If this is what
the D.T. S are like...

21:10.378 --> 21:13.646
I'm gonna give up
the bottle for life.

21:13.646 --> 21:19.021
The mind plays funny tricks
on you all the time.

21:19.021 --> 21:23.824
You know that, George.
Come on. Relax. It's okay. Relax

21:25.931 --> 21:28.422
That sure is a pretty song.

21:29.135 --> 21:31.069
Yes, it is.

21:35.206 --> 21:37.800
You're very beautiful, Hilly.

21:41.446 --> 21:43.277
I like you too, George.

23:02.859 --> 23:04.349
Hilly, wake up.

23:05.895 --> 23:07.226
Hi, George.

23:07.226 --> 23:12.233
Hilly, the man that I saw outside
the window last night... this is him.

23:12.233 --> 23:16.533
- That's my boss. That's Professor Schreiner.
- I know it. That's what I'm talking about.

23:16.533 --> 23:18.540
- What time is it, George?
- It's just after 8:00.

23:18.540 --> 23:22.703
8:00? Oh, no. Wake me up again
when it's after 10:00.

23:22.703 --> 23:24.335
Hilly, this man
has been murdered.

23:26.515 --> 23:27.846
- Well...

23:28.917 --> 23:32.910
Why don't you go down the hall
and discuss it with him?

23:32.910 --> 23:35.115
And then come back here
and discuss it with me.

23:35.115 --> 23:38.591
He's just right past
the diner, room "C."

23:38.591 --> 23:40.184
Hilly, I didn't imagine it.

23:41.329 --> 23:44.924
Good night, George.
You're a wonderful gardener.

24:16.697 --> 24:18.289
- Rapist.
- Oh!

24:19.833 --> 24:23.599
Hey, George, you devil.
Come on. Join me for coffee.

24:23.599 --> 24:27.334
All right. I'll be right back.
I just have to check on something.

24:31.210 --> 24:32.302
What is that?

24:47.427 --> 24:49.452
Yeah? What do you want?

24:49.452 --> 24:51.997
I'd like to see
Professor Schreiner, please.

24:51.997 --> 24:56.559
- Yeah? Who are you?
- My name is George Caldwell.

24:56.559 --> 24:58.570
You a friend of the professor?

24:58.570 --> 25:02.506
No, not exactly. I'm a friend of his secretary's.
We were a little worried about him.

25:03.208 --> 25:05.438
Yeah? What are you worried about?

25:06.845 --> 25:09.109
Can't I talk to the professor?

25:11.750 --> 25:13.308
What are you doing in there?

25:13.308 --> 25:15.819
I think you're sticking your nose in
where it don't belong.

25:15.819 --> 25:18.185
You and that broad are gonna
get yourself in trouble.

25:18.185 --> 25:20.520
In fact, she's already in trouble

25:20.520 --> 25:23.152
- You're the one who's in trouble,
mister, not me.
- Reace!

25:23.152 --> 25:25.423
Get rid of this bum.

25:26.898 --> 25:28.832
What are you doing?
Who is that?

25:28.832 --> 25:33.360
Hey! Listen, you big lummox,
let me go! What the hell are you doing?

25:33.360 --> 25:36.805
Are you crazy?
What the hell's the matter with you?

25:36.805 --> 25:40.002
All right, listen, buster, you're in trouble...
and I mean big trouble,

25:40.002 --> 25:41.738
because I'm reporting you.

25:43.147 --> 25:46.514
Oh, no, you can't be serious.
Wait a minute. All right. Enough's enough.

25:46.514 --> 25:49.781
If you're willing to forget it...
I don't believe this! Are you kidding?

26:03.100 --> 26:04.692
Goddamn it!

26:05.736 --> 26:07.995
Son of a bitch!

26:49.578 --> 26:51.239
This is terrific!

28:03.383 --> 28:07.979
- If that's you, Pepe, you're in one heap of trouble.
- No, it's not Pepe.

28:07.979 --> 28:11.353
- Where's Pepe?
- I don't know. My name is George...

28:11.353 --> 28:14.860
Goddamn it, I knew it! He's gone off
again with that no accountin' Manuel.

28:14.860 --> 28:17.897
- My name is George Caldwell.
- Those two get together, smoke a little weed.

28:17.897 --> 28:21.092
Next thing you know, they're off
buzzing the turkeys in the pickup.

28:21.092 --> 28:23.568
- Excuse me, dear.
- I should've fired him 30 years ago.

28:23.568 --> 28:26.037
Excuse me.
Do you think I could use your telephone?

28:26.037 --> 28:27.835
- Telephone?
- Yes.

28:27.835 --> 28:31.071
- You ain't from around here, are you?
- No, I'm lost.

28:31.071 --> 28:33.668
I'm not lost, but I was
thrown off of the Silver Streak.

28:33.668 --> 28:35.475
Thrown off? That a fact?

28:35.475 --> 28:38.108
Tell me, is there a woman in this?

28:39.418 --> 28:41.818
- Well, there's a girl, but...
- I knew it.

28:42.755 --> 28:45.349
No, no, no. It's nothing to do
with what you're thinking.

28:45.349 --> 28:49.554
Actually, she's in a great deal of danger.
That's why I have to use your telephone...

28:49.554 --> 28:51.755
so I can call the police and have those
people who threw me off the train arrested.

28:51.755 --> 28:55.426
- Well, it sounds like you're in an awful hurry.
- I am. That's what I'm trying to tell you.

28:55.426 --> 28:58.595
That suits me just fine...
'cause I'm running a little bit late myself.

28:58.595 --> 29:02.198
- Tell you what, Steve.
- George. George Caldwell.

29:02.198 --> 29:04.242
- Rita Babtree.
- How do you do?

29:04.242 --> 29:08.746
If you'll finish milking old Harriet over there...
I'll go in and change and you can ride into town with me.

29:08.746 --> 29:11.179
- Oh, great!
- The sheriff's a good friend of mine.

29:11.179 --> 29:13.376
Wonderful. Just tell me
what I have to do.

29:13.376 --> 29:16.648
Well, you just take
this bucket and milk her.

29:16.648 --> 29:19.747
Milk her?
I've never milked a cow before.

29:19.747 --> 29:23.726
Cut the gas, Steve.
You're a grown man.

29:23.726 --> 29:25.990
I'm sure you've had
some similar experience.

29:28.499 --> 29:30.490
Look, you just sit down...

29:30.490 --> 29:33.059
take a tit in each hand and
let nature take its course.

29:33.059 --> 29:34.365
All right.

29:34.365 --> 29:36.270
These cows are so full...

29:36.270 --> 29:39.242
it's like tapping a trip valve
on Niagara Falls.

29:39.242 --> 29:42.210
- I'll go in and change and meet you
outside in 10 minutes.
- All right.

29:42.210 --> 29:44.110
I'll do my best.

29:45.148 --> 29:46.672
Hello.

29:51.021 --> 29:52.579
Let's see.

29:53.790 --> 29:56.224
Just be nice.
Be nice.

29:56.224 --> 29:58.591
Wait a minute.

29:59.663 --> 30:02.791
Something's wrong.
You've got four of them.

30:06.169 --> 30:09.195
Oop.! Come on, Harriet.
Come on. Give me a break.

30:10.741 --> 30:13.938
Nice, fresh milk.
Here it comes.

30:14.978 --> 30:18.777
Nothing's coming out though.
Here we go.

30:18.777 --> 30:23.649
All right, now, I know I'm a slow
starter, but where's Niagara Falls?

30:27.590 --> 30:29.615
Hey, Steve, whatcha doin'?

30:29.615 --> 30:32.661
I was just looking at my schedule
for the Silver Streak.

30:32.661 --> 30:35.128
No, I don't mean that. I mean...

30:35.128 --> 30:38.394
why are you sittin' in that car?
We ain't goin' in that.

30:38.394 --> 30:41.061
- We aren't?
- No!

30:41.061 --> 30:44.573
Come on, Steve.
Follow me.

30:50.645 --> 30:53.580
Put these packages
in the front seat...

30:53.580 --> 30:55.809
and I'll get the wheel blocks.

30:55.809 --> 30:58.614
I sure hope Pepe
filled it with enough gas.

30:58.614 --> 31:00.922
We're not going in that, are we?

31:00.922 --> 31:03.421
What's the matter?
You afraid of flyin'?

31:03.421 --> 31:06.016
No, no.
I'm not afraid.

31:06.016 --> 31:09.859
Great, 'cause it ain't no fun
soarin' with a turkey.

31:16.404 --> 31:18.964
Look out for the windmill.
Look out for the windmill!

31:25.712 --> 31:28.681
- You okay with those packages?
- Yeah, I guess so.

31:28.681 --> 31:33.208
Well, it won't be long. We should be
in Stavely by 2:00.

31:34.621 --> 31:39.058
2:00? That's two and a half hours from now.
Where's Stavely?

31:39.058 --> 31:42.253
Sixty miles
the other side of Albuquerque.

31:43.163 --> 31:45.324
- Wait a minute.
- What'd you say?

31:47.067 --> 31:50.400
The Silver Streak
stops there at 2:27.

31:50.400 --> 31:54.065
If we got there by 2:00 the sheriff
could meet the train when it arrives.

31:54.065 --> 31:56.074
Yeah, I suppose so.

31:56.074 --> 31:59.077
- This is fabulous!
- Ain't it the truth?

31:59.077 --> 32:04.138
They talk of the joy of sex,
but it don't last like the fun of flyin'.

32:23.569 --> 32:26.037
Look! There's the Silver Streak.!

32:45.723 --> 32:48.749
- I think we're going to make it.
- Look at those sheep down there.

32:48.749 --> 32:52.887
Don't they make a lovely sight?
I'm just itchin'to buzz 'em.

32:52.887 --> 32:54.488
To do what?

32:54.488 --> 32:57.398
- You never buzzed sheep?
- I don't think so.

32:57.398 --> 32:59.595
Hold on, Steve!
We're going in!

33:12.182 --> 33:14.173
Look at those little critters run.!

33:17.187 --> 33:20.088
Come on.! Let's buzz 'em again.!
Whoo-hoo.!

33:32.736 --> 33:34.931
Here we are.

33:34.931 --> 33:38.133
- Hello, Rita.
- Hi, Burt. Is the sheriff in?

33:38.133 --> 33:40.574
- He's over at Clancey's Dairy.
He'll be back in about...

33:40.574 --> 33:42.908
Look!
There's the Silver Streak.!

33:43.979 --> 33:46.641
- Thank you. Thank you, Rita.
- Don't you wanna go get the sheriff?

33:46.641 --> 33:50.811
- No time! Thank you, dear. Good-bye.!
- So long, Steve.

33:57.259 --> 34:00.524
This time, try to stay on!

34:00.524 --> 34:02.563
Come on! Come on!

34:02.563 --> 34:05.361
Jump up! Jump!

34:07.269 --> 34:08.827
You got it!

34:09.938 --> 34:11.735
All right!

34:17.580 --> 34:19.103
Hey, welcome aboard.

34:19.103 --> 34:21.909
- Don't you just love train travel?
- I love it.

34:21.909 --> 34:23.610
- Loves it.

34:56.150 --> 34:59.608
I asked you to join me for breakfast.
This is lunch.

34:59.608 --> 35:01.881
Sorry. I lost track of time.

35:04.558 --> 35:06.685
Well, what were you doin' back there?

35:06.685 --> 35:08.751
Gettin' a little ass?

35:09.663 --> 35:11.858
No, I was squeezing tits.

35:14.001 --> 35:16.162
You are a sexy devil, aren't you?

35:16.870 --> 35:19.964
Kind of worked up a sweat too,
didn't ya, you horny bastard?

35:24.344 --> 35:26.005
Well, what do you expect?

35:26.005 --> 35:28.410
I mean, she's a hot little number.

35:28.410 --> 35:30.711
And he's very heavy competition.

35:30.711 --> 35:32.774
You know him?

35:32.774 --> 35:36.117
Doesn't everybody know him?
That's Roger Devereau.

35:36.117 --> 35:39.955
He's Chicago's own jet-setter.

35:39.955 --> 35:43.018
I mean, you know, he's a big cheese on
the Art Institute, something like that.

35:43.018 --> 35:45.620
Like I say, very heavy competition.

35:46.465 --> 35:48.228
Are you gonna take him on?

36:42.586 --> 36:44.349
Are you all right?

36:50.394 --> 36:52.055
What's the matter?

36:54.131 --> 36:56.998
- Honey, what's the matter?
- What's the matter?

36:58.168 --> 36:59.829
Who left who?

36:59.829 --> 37:03.669
Last time I saw you, you were
gonna go visit the professor.

37:03.669 --> 37:06.539
- Hilly, the professor is dead.
I'm sure of it.

37:06.539 --> 37:08.043
Listen to me.

37:08.043 --> 37:10.478
I went to his room
this morning, and he wasn't there.

37:10.478 --> 37:13.640
Two dumb thugs
were looking through his things.

37:13.640 --> 37:16.708
They pushed me out of his room
and threw me off the train.

37:16.708 --> 37:19.380
-Threw you off?
-The point is they were searching for something.

37:19.380 --> 37:23.118
I don't know what, but they've killed
the professor for it and now I'm
positive they're gonna go after you

37:23.118 --> 37:26.320
We've gotta get off the train
and contact the police.

37:26.320 --> 37:29.991
- No, George, you've got it all mixed up.
- I don't have it mixed up.

37:29.991 --> 37:32.227
I'm just worried about you.

37:37.807 --> 37:39.934
Hello, Roger.

37:39.934 --> 37:42.739
This is my friend George Caldwell.
Roger Devereau.

37:44.380 --> 37:48.042
- How do you do?
- George has just been telling me
how he'd been thrown off the train.

37:49.117 --> 37:53.281
Oh, you're the one? I'm so pleased
to see you. Are you all right?

37:53.281 --> 37:55.152
- Yes, I'm fine.
- Oh, that's good news.

37:55.152 --> 37:58.681
As soon as I was told,
I contacted the police in Albuquerque...

37:58.681 --> 38:01.991
and told them to spare no expense
to make sure you were safe.

38:01.991 --> 38:05.261
Reace... he's like a child... got off
the train and tried to find you...

38:05.261 --> 38:06.995
say he was sorry.

38:06.995 --> 38:09.560
- How did you get back on?
- Who's Reace?

38:09.560 --> 38:11.731
He's the one that threw you off.

38:13.342 --> 38:17.574
You must remember him... a large man
with not very attractive dental work.

38:17.574 --> 38:20.513
I do remember,
but what does he got to do with you?

38:20.513 --> 38:22.845
He works for me.
He's my chauffeur.

38:22.845 --> 38:25.442
Not very bright,
but extremely loyal.

38:25.442 --> 38:29.649
And naturally, I assume total
responsibility for all his actions...

38:29.649 --> 38:32.591
and will pay for any damages.

38:32.591 --> 38:35.527
And what about that other fellow?

38:35.527 --> 38:38.895
I met another man this morning.
Does he work for you too?

38:39.700 --> 38:43.295
Oh, yes, of course.
You don't know the entire story, do you?

38:43.295 --> 38:47.808
Early this morning, I was having
breakfast with Professor Schreiner...

38:47.808 --> 38:51.971
and he wanted to show me some
important papers connected with his book.

38:51.971 --> 38:54.446
But, unfortunately, they were missing

38:54.446 --> 38:57.642
So we searched
his compartment twice...

38:57.642 --> 39:01.084
and eventually we discovered them
in his trunk in the baggage room.

39:01.084 --> 39:04.914
t was something of an upset,
but if you know the professor....

39:04.914 --> 39:08.193
you'll know he's slightly
absent-minded.

39:08.193 --> 39:10.229
Mr. Devereau, I'm very confused.

39:10.229 --> 39:13.493
I don't understand how you could've
had breakfast with Professor Schreiner.

39:13.493 --> 39:16.296
George thinks
the professor's been murdered.

39:19.105 --> 39:21.266
- Murdered?
- That's right, last night.

39:21.266 --> 39:23.138
That's extraordinary.
Why should you think that?

39:23.138 --> 39:27.873
Because I saw him fall off the roof
of this train just outside this window.

39:27.873 --> 39:31.143
- He was shot in the head.
- You were in this compartment?

39:31.143 --> 39:33.548
I was lying right here.

39:34.853 --> 39:38.050
Hilly, you'll have to go back to
my compartment, straighten it out.

39:38.050 --> 39:41.490
That man Whiney doesn't know
what he's doing. Devereau.

39:41.490 --> 39:44.688
Mr. Caldwell, allow me to introduce
Professor Schreiner.

39:44.688 --> 39:46.993
Professor Schreiner, Mr. Caldwell.

39:46.993 --> 39:49.898
- Hello.
- How do you do?

39:49.898 --> 39:51.697
What did you do to your jacket?

39:51.697 --> 39:56.139
Mr. Caldwell is the man that Reace
inadvertently threw off the train.

39:56.139 --> 39:58.642
Oh, yes.

39:58.642 --> 40:03.443
That stupid person.
I do hope you weren't hurt.

40:03.443 --> 40:05.482
No, no.
I'm all right.

40:05.482 --> 40:09.350
I suppose I'm to blame
for this morning's fracas.

40:09.350 --> 40:13.857
After all, none of this would've happened
if I hadn't misplaced the Rembrandt letters.

40:13.857 --> 40:14.577
The what?

40:16.027 --> 40:20.020
It doesn't matter. I'm so glad that you're
all right and managed to get back on the train.

40:20.020 --> 40:23.225
Oh, Professor? Professor,
I put back as much... I put back...

40:24.368 --> 40:26.928
Hey, how'd you get here?

40:26.928 --> 40:31.498
Mr. Caldwell, allow me to introduce
an associate of mine, Mr. Whiney.

40:31.498 --> 40:34.977
If an apology is due, I'm sure
that he'd be prepared to make it.

40:34.977 --> 40:38.072
It's a pity that Reace
is not here to do the same.

40:38.072 --> 40:40.582
Reace, that moron.
It was all his fault.

40:40.582 --> 40:43.380
I was looking for the papers.
I never touched you, did I?

40:43.380 --> 40:45.216
- No, no.
- See?

40:45.216 --> 40:50.055
It's been very hectic for me.
I think I'll have a scotch and lie down.

40:50.055 --> 40:54.654
- Why don't you use my compartment?
- Thank you. I will.

40:54.654 --> 40:57.757
Hilly...
will you help him with that mess?

40:58.502 --> 41:01.528
Mr. Caldwell,
it's been nice meeting you.

41:01.528 --> 41:04.836
I hope the rest of the trip for both
of us is a little less exhilarating.

41:04.836 --> 41:06.705
Let's hope so.

41:08.378 --> 41:12.508
Well, I think I've made a silly fool
of myself this morning.

41:12.508 --> 41:14.242
- No, no, not at all.
- No, no, I did.

41:14.242 --> 41:19.049
I was just sticking my nose into a lot
of stuff that's none of my business..

41:19.049 --> 41:22.249
and coming up with some crazy ideas.
You were right.

41:23.359 --> 41:26.294
I guess I was imagining
a lot of things last night.

41:27.463 --> 41:28.953
Probably the champagne.

41:32.668 --> 41:35.694
- Well
- Let me clean your jacket..

41:35.694 --> 41:38.467
Oh, that's all right.
I have another one.

41:38.467 --> 41:41.942
We get to Chicago tomorrow and
I did come on this trip to do some work.

41:41.942 --> 41:43.706
So I'll say good-bye.

41:43.706 --> 41:47.306
- Couldn't you possibly join us for dinner?
- Oh, yes, do.

41:48.584 --> 41:51.143
Thanks. No.
I think I'll just eat in my room.

41:58.526 --> 42:01.393
This latch...
seems to be stuck.

42:03.298 --> 42:05.823
I'll get the porter
to fix it right away.

42:37.130 --> 42:39.894
What are you up to there, lover boy?

42:39.894 --> 42:41.958
Hello, Bob Sweet.

42:42.636 --> 42:44.627
- Hello, Bobby.
- How are ya?

42:46.006 --> 42:47.234
I'm all right.

42:47.234 --> 42:51.209
Better yet, uh, what are you?
A miniature alcoholic?

42:51.209 --> 42:54.509
Did you know that
the Blanard Tunnel...

42:54.509 --> 42:57.049
was the highest point on this line?

42:57.049 --> 42:58.413
Yeah, I knew that.

42:58.413 --> 43:01.647
Did you know that when we reach it,
I intend to be higher?

43:02.521 --> 43:05.319
- Just don't fall off, huh? Okay?
- Oh, no.

43:05.319 --> 43:08.986
I've left this train once already.
That's enough.

43:08.986 --> 43:11.689
You have? What do you mean?

43:11.689 --> 43:14.062
Last night...

43:14.062 --> 43:16.727
just as I was about to...

43:17.837 --> 43:20.499
kiss my beautiful blonde...

43:20.499 --> 43:23.838
I saw her boss
hanging outside the window.

43:23.838 --> 43:26.173
Wait. You saw her boss,
Professor Schreiner, huh?

43:26.173 --> 43:27.974
That's him.

43:27.974 --> 43:29.947
That's the fellow.

43:29.947 --> 43:32.041
He was shot in the head.

43:33.685 --> 43:36.176
I knew that
I had been drinking...

43:36.176 --> 43:38.916
so I went to see
the professor this morning...

43:38.916 --> 43:41.754
and I found this
little weasel of a guy in his room.

43:41.754 --> 43:44.158
- Edgar Whiney.
- That's him.

43:44.158 --> 43:47.687
- How did you know that?
- Oh, I-I know. I just know.

43:47.687 --> 43:49.757
Go on, go on.

43:49.757 --> 43:52.564
Well, then this huge mountain...

43:52.564 --> 43:55.367
with a gold mine stuck in his gums...

43:55.367 --> 43:59.501
picked me up and
threw me off the train.

43:59.501 --> 44:03.013
- What... But you never saw the professor, huh?
- No, I saw him.

44:03.013 --> 44:05.379
- I saw him this afternoon.
- Where?

44:05.379 --> 44:07.384
In Hilly's compartment.

44:07.384 --> 44:11.285
See, the man I saw last night
was a hallucination.

44:12.222 --> 44:14.713
- What did he look like?
- Who?

44:14.713 --> 44:17.226
The professor, you know,
that you saw this afternoon.

44:17.226 --> 44:19.387
Like his picture.

44:19.387 --> 44:24.127
- Did he say anything to you?
- Why are you asking me all these questions?

44:24.127 --> 44:26.692
- Did he say anything...
- Nothing, nothing.

44:26.692 --> 44:28.897
He was tired
and wanted to have a scotch.

44:29.807 --> 44:33.174
You don't have any ice in your drink.
- That's it! Scotch!

44:34.244 --> 44:37.236
Listen. See, you didn't have
a hallucination.

44:38.248 --> 44:40.216
The professor's been murdered.

44:40.216 --> 44:43.081
The guy you saw this afternoon
was a fake.

44:43.081 --> 44:44.881
Oh, no.

44:44.881 --> 44:49.084
Yeah. Listen, I talked to the real
professor last night. I mean it.

44:49.084 --> 44:51.854
He didn't wanna have anything
to do with Mr. Devereau.

44:51.854 --> 44:54.658
Besides that, he's a health nut.
Doesn't touch alcohol.

44:54.658 --> 44:58.360
Oh, Bobby, just because
you're a vitamin salesman?

44:58.360 --> 45:01.096
My name is Stevens.
I'm a federal agent.

45:04.240 --> 45:07.073
We've been working on this case
for two and a half years.

45:08.044 --> 45:10.137
Well, what are you tailing
the professor for?

45:10.137 --> 45:13.273
I am not tailing the professor,
I'm tailing Devereau.

45:13.273 --> 45:14.611
Come on. Let's go.

45:14.611 --> 45:17.174
Wait a minute. What about Hilly?

45:17.174 --> 45:20.153
Don't worry about it. They're not
gonna kill her till we get to Chicago.

45:20.153 --> 45:22.918
I don't even think they'll try
to kill you till then. Come on.

45:25.527 --> 45:28.121
Devereau's men must've brought the
professor back here...

45:28.121 --> 45:30.027
after 9:00 pm last night.

45:30.027 --> 45:33.829
- How do you figure that?
- Because I left him at 9:00 pm.

45:33.829 --> 45:38.362
And because this is the easiest access
to the roof. Somehow, he must've escaped.

45:38.362 --> 45:41.967
He got out to this ladder, then ran back
down the train before they shot him.

45:45.647 --> 45:48.343
You're not going up there, are you?

45:48.343 --> 45:51.976
Yeah. The Blanard Tunnel is up ahead.

45:51.976 --> 45:54.714
Come on up and
keep a lookout, will ya?

45:54.714 --> 45:56.848
All right, I'll try.

46:37.029 --> 46:39.088
What did you find?

46:39.088 --> 46:41.098
It was hooked on
a protruding bolt.

46:44.102 --> 46:47.333
Then I was right.
I did see him.

46:59.785 --> 47:05.017
I'll bet Devereau has already got the body
picked up and placed in cold storage someplace.

47:06.090 --> 47:08.888
Too bad.
He was a sweet old guy.

47:08.888 --> 47:11.689
Buy why did he have
to kill the professor?

47:11.689 --> 47:15.630
He was going to be embarrassed
by the findings in the professor's book.

47:17.001 --> 47:19.060
Two of the institute's Rembrandts...

47:19.060 --> 47:22.003
both bought and authenticated
by Devereau...

47:22.003 --> 47:24.166
were going to be proved forgeries.

47:25.242 --> 47:28.439
The professor had the proof
in his possession.

47:29.547 --> 47:31.879
I asked him last night,
"What was the proof?"

47:32.817 --> 47:36.718
He told me I was going
to have to wait for his lecture.

47:36.718 --> 47:38.777
And Devereau wasn't going to wait.

47:41.124 --> 47:44.560
I think the idea
was to kidnap the professor...

47:44.560 --> 47:46.618
then kill him...

47:46.618 --> 47:50.063
and then substitute
some phony look-alike...

47:50.063 --> 47:52.863
who would botch the lecture
and discredit the book.

47:54.337 --> 47:57.795
- We've gotta find the proof.
- But they have the proof.

47:57.795 --> 48:00.707
They have it. That's what Whiney
and everyone was looking for this morning...

48:00.707 --> 48:02.244
the Rembrandt letters.

48:02.244 --> 48:05.873
They said that they found them
in the professor's trunk.

48:05.873 --> 48:08.918
They're lying. That's the first place
they would've looked...

48:08.918 --> 48:12.385
before they started turning
his room upside down.

48:13.722 --> 48:16.782
No! No, the professor hid them
someplace, somewhere simple...

48:16.782 --> 48:20.056
as a precaution when he found out
Devereau was on the train.

48:20.056 --> 48:22.689
My God! I know where they are!
Come on! Come on!

48:46.788 --> 48:48.779
The Rembrandt letters.

48:51.058 --> 48:53.720
Holy Toledo!
I think you've found it.

48:55.763 --> 48:58.823
This is the genuine article,
penned by the old boy himself, huh?

48:58.823 --> 49:02.495
"Rembrandt Harmenszoon Van Rijn. "

49:03.971 --> 49:06.963
Yeah. My guess is there's a fact there's
some kind of a date in all this...

49:06.963 --> 49:09.771
that proves the charges the professor
